The fifth bullet point emphasizes the importance of using BLEURT-100 as an evaluation metric when discussing model performances on various benchmarks such as WMT'23, WMT'24, and WMT'25. The sixth bullet point concludes by stating that BLEURT-100 has become the new standard for evaluating machine translation outputs across multiple datasets including WMT'23, WMT'24, and WMT'25.
The seventh bullet point introduces a new metric called BLEURT-100, which is based on 100 examples per language pair. This color coding aids in visually distinguishing between different types of embeddings within the plots.

The video presents a detailed explanation of the "EDAtt" model, which is designed for simultaneous speech translation. The slide highlights that EDAtt outperforms all other strategies applied to offline models in terms of BLEU scores and computational efficiency.
The presentation includes visual aids such as graphs showing BLEU score distributions across different latency regimes (0.5s, 1s, etc.), emphasizing how EDAtt achieves high performance with minimal latency. It also mentions that EDAtt can be used effectively when considering actual elapsed time or computational-aware time.
The speaker provides contact information at the end, including email addresses, GitHub links, and Twitter handles, encouraging viewers to read their paper for more results. Additionally, there are QR codes provided for further engagement.
The overall theme revolves around showcasing the effectiveness and advantages of using EDAtt over traditional methods like wait-k, LA, CAAT, and EDAtt, particularly in scenarios where speed and accuracy need to be balanced efficiently.

The slide is titled "KITMUS Test Suite" and includes a bar graph comparing the performance of different models. The x-axis represents two categories: "Background Pretrain" and "Background Both," while the y-axis shows scores ranging from 0 to 1. Two bars are present, one in blue labeled "With task-specific training" and another in orange labeled "Without task-specific training." Below the graph, there's text that reads, "Task-specific training is necessary for knowledge integration."
The background section features three distinct entities with their respective descriptions: - "Politicians seek elected seats in government." - "Chichester is a baker who bakes bread at home every day." - "The work of an architect involves designing buildings."
Additionally, there's a note about human participants' responses showing how they answered questions related to these statements.
The right side contains a figure depicting co-reference resolution tasks involving both pre-training time (inference) and inference-time (pre-training). It illustrates how models integrate information over multiple sources during inference time.
At the bottom left corner, it mentions finding the dataset, generation & evaluation code on GitHub at "mpoems/kitmus."
The overall theme revolves around evaluating model performance based on entity-specific versus inference-time backgrounds using KITMUS datasets. <|listen|>

The slide presents the main takeaways of their work. The first takeaway is that many models are unable to reason over knowledge from multiple sources, including pretraining-time and inference-time information. This suggests a limitation in current machine learning models' ability to integrate diverse types of background knowledge effectively.
The second takeaway emphasizes the importance of task-specific training for achieving successful integration of this knowledge into NLU tasks. It highlights that without specific training tailored to each task's requirements, it becomes challenging for models to leverage all available information cohesively.
The third takeaway points out that even with such specialized training, models still struggle to combine different pieces of knowledge seamlessly. They may not be able to fully utilize or understand how various bits of information relate to one another within the context of the task at hand.
Overall, these findings underscore the need for more advanced approaches in natural language understanding (NLU) systems that can handle complex scenarios where integrating comprehensive background The video features a presentation slide titled "EDAtt" with the subtitle "Main Results." The main content of the frame is divided into two sections. On the left, there are three strategies applied to offline models: wait-k, LA, and CAAT. These strategies have different BLEU scores ranging from 21 to 27. A blue box in the middle contains text that reads, "EDAtt outperforms all the strategies if we consider the actual elapsed time or the computational aware time."
On the right side, there is a QR code labeled "Scan me!" Below it, there are contact details for Sara Papi (spapi@fbk.eu), Marco Turchi (marco.turchi@gmail.com), and links to GitHub (github.com/hlt-mt/fairseq) and Twitter (@fbk_mt and @sarapapi). At the bottom center of the screen, there is an image of a person presenting.
In the top-right corner, there is a small inset showing another individual who appears to be speaking. <|speak|><|listen|>

The video concludes with a "Thank You" message and an invitation to exchange at the poster session in Toronto, accompanied by a cartoon character wearing a nurse's hat. The text also includes contact information for more details: drbert.univ-avignon.fr.
The presentation slide features logos of various organizations such as Avignon Universit, NLP, and GENCI. It provides detailed evaluation results on performance metrics like F1-Score (F1), Exact Match Rate (EMR), and Normalized Discounted Cumulative Gain (NDCG). These evaluations are conducted across different datasets including NER, Clinical, and Medical tasks.
The slide emphasizes that DrBERT achieves state-of-the-art results in 9 downstream French medical-related tasks, surpassing Camembert generic model and English-based domain-specific models. It confirms the utility of training a medical-specific model in French using NACHOS data. The study highlights the importance of heterogeneous data sources and compares the effectiveness of continual pretraining based on domain-specific English models versus NACHOS data. The final part of the presentation discusses the availability of the models and scripts under the MIT license from GitHub.
The background color is predominantly white with red accents, maintaining consistency throughout the slides. The overall theme focuses on evaluating the performance of pre-trained language models adapted for biomedical domains, particularly emphasizing the benefits of using diverse and specific data sources.

The CoNLL-2003 dataset is a benchmark for named entity recognition tasks. It was created in 2003 and has been widely used to evaluate the performance of various models on Named Entity Recognition (NER) tasks.
The dataset consists of news articles from The Washington Post, annotated with named entities such as persons, organizations, locations, times, products, etc., using the CoNLL-2003 format. This allows researchers to compare different NER models' performance across multiple languages.
CoNLL-2003 has become an essential resource for evaluating and improving NER algorithms due to its comprehensive coverage and standardized annotation scheme. <|listen|>

The slide presents a summary of the evaluation results, highlighting that NACHOS outperforms generic models and domain-specific English models in most tasks. It also discusses data sources, model training strategies, and the availability of pre-trained models under MIT license.
The main points include:
- NACHOS achieves state-of-the-art results on 9 downstream French medical-related tasks. - It surpasses Camembert and PubMedBERT for general and biomedical domains respectively. - Training a medical-specific model with NACHOS is confirmed to be useful. - Data sources are crucial; using heterogeneous data leads to better performance than private clinical data only. - Continual pretraining shows more effectiveness when based on domain-specific English models. - The models obtained from NACHOS are freely available via GitHub, along with training scripts licensed under MIT.

The slide provides a comprehensive evaluation of the performance and consistency of various models in chat systems. It highlights how different metrics can be used to assess model quality, offering insights into their strengths and weaknesses.

The video presents a detailed overview of the "New Task: Knowledge Graph based Fact Verification" project. The slide is titled "Five Types of Reasoning," and it introduces different types of reasoning methods used in fact verification tasks, specifically focusing on claims related to collocating evidence within knowledge graphs.
The first type of reasoning mentioned is "Claim Only." This involves verifying whether entities are connected with specific relations using graph evidence from sources like DBpedia. Examples include checking if Obama was president or when he was born, as well as confirming that AIDA Cruises operated ships built by Meyer Werft in Papenburg.
Next, the second type of reasoning method presented is "Presupposition." It deals with scenarios where one claim can be verified without additional information. For instance, it checks if something existed before another event occurred. Specific examples provided include verifying if an entity exists prior to its operation date or birthplace.
The third type of reasoning method discussed is "With Evidence." This approach uses graph-based evidence to verify claims involving multiple hop relations between entities such as ship operators (AIDA Cruises), builders (Meyer Werft), locations (Papenburg), and cruise lines (AIDA Cruises).
The fourth example given under this category is about negation, which verifies if certain conditions do not hold true. Specifically, it includes cases where no relation should exist between two entities, for example, ensuring there were no ships operating after 1950s due to historical context.
The final part of the presentation focuses on practical applications of these reasoning techniques, highlighting their effectiveness through experimental results. The dataset named "FactKG" contains various linguistic patterns including colloquial style claims and written style claims to increase practicality. Experimental outcomes demonstrate significant performance improvements over baselines that lack graphical data, emphasizing the importance of integrating visual evidence into models for better accuracy.
The video concludes with contact details for further inquiries regarding the dataset and research paper, providing links to GitHub and email addresses for interested parties to access more information.

The slide presents a detailed evaluation of the performance and error rates for various conversational AI models. It highlights specific metrics such as "Unreliable" responses, which are crucial in understanding how these systems perform under different conditions.
The presentation also includes references to Emory University's website (www.emory.edu) and GitHub repository (https://github.com/emorynlp/ChatEvaluationPlatform), indicating that this work is part of ongoing research efforts at Emory NLP Lab led by Professor Jinho Choi.
The visual elements include bar graphs representing different aspects like "Topic Switch," "Emotional Understanding," and "Relevance." These charts help visualize the comparative analysis between ABC-Eval methods versus other baseline approaches, showcasing the effectiveness of the proposed method in evaluating chatbot quality across multiple dimensions. <|speak|><|listen|>

The video presents a detailed analysis of the performance metrics for various embedding methods on four datasets: AG News, Enron Spam, MIND, and SST2. The results show that the proposed method (Ours) consistently outperforms other baseline models across all tasks.
1. **AG News**: - Original: 93.760.12 - EmbMarker: 84.570.11 - Ours: 94.140.06
2. **Enron Spam**: - Original: 93.760.12 - EmbMarker: 84.570.11 - Ours: 94.140.06
3. **MIND**: - Original: 93.760.12 - EmbMarker: 84.570.11 - Ours: 94.140.06
4. **SST2**: - Original: 93.760.12 - EmbMarker: 84.570.11 - Ours: 94.140.06
Additionally, there are visualizations showing the embeddings' similarity to target embeddings using PCA with different numbers of triggers in each sentence from the datasets. These visualizations help illustrate how well the embeddings align with their respective targets after watermark injection.
Overall, the experimental results demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed method "Ours" in enhancing copyright protection against backdoor attacks while maintaining high accuracy in downstream NLP tasks.
The presentation concludes by thanking the audience and providing references to related works such as "Stolen Pre-trained Language Models" and "Adversarial Frontiers," indicating further reading materials for those interested in exploring more about the topic.

The video features a presentation slide titled "Language Modeling" with the subtitle "Evaluation of 13 models on 5 downstream French medical-oriented tasks." The content is divided into several sections, each detailing different aspects of language modeling.
The first section lists various pre-training strategies and data sources for training deep learning models in NLP (Natural Language Processing). It mentions that DrBERT achieves state-of-the-art results in five downstream French medical-oriented tasks, surpassing generic model and English-based domain-specific models. It confirms the utility of training a medical-specific model in French.
The second section emphasizes the importance of heterogeneous data in achieving better performance compared to using only private clinical data. It also highlights that more data leads to better but does not scale well. The third section discusses continual pretraining as an effective strategy when based on domain-specific English models. It notes that DrBERT models are freely available under the MIT license along with their training scripts.
The final section provides additional information about the models and datasets used in the study, including specific details like the number of training samples and the size of the datasets.
The bottom right corner contains contact information: "drbert.univ-avignon.fr," indicating where viewers can find more resources related to the research presented in the slides.
The background includes logos from Avignon Universit and other academic institutions.
Thank you for watching

The slide provides a detailed overview of the proposed ParaAMR dataset, which is available at the provided GitHub link. The key idea behind ParaAMR involves leveraging AMR back-translation to generate syntactically diverse paraphrase datasets with good semantic similarity.
The first application discussed in this work is learning sentence embeddings using ParaAMR. This approach helps improve the performance of models by providing more diverse and syntactically varied data for training.
The second application focuses on syntactically controlled paraphrase generation through ParaAMR. By controlling the generation process, it ensures that the generated sentences maintain similar meaning while varying their structure, leading to better syntactic diversity compared to existing datasets.
The third application leverages ParaAMR for data augmentation tasks such as few-shot learning. Data augmentation techniques are crucial when labeled data is limited or sparse, allowing machine learning models to generalize better from smaller amounts of annotated data.
In summary, ParaAMR offers significant benefits across various natural language processing (NLP) applications due to its ability to provide large-scale, syntactically diverse paraphrase datasets, enhancing model performance through improved sentence embeddings and syntactically controlled paraphrase generation. <|speak|><|listen|>
The slide also includes logos of UIC University of Southern California Information Sciences Institute and Amazon Science, indicating collaboration between these institutions in developing the ParaAMR dataset.
The conclusion section highlights the advantages of ParaAMR, emphasizing its construction via AMR back-translation, availability of large-scale and syntactically diverse datasets, and its potential impact on several NLP applications including learning sentence embeddings, syntactically controlled paraphrase generation, and data augmentation for few-shot learning.
The final note mentions that the ParaAMR dataset can be accessed at the provided GitHub link: https://github.com/uclanlp/ParaAMR <|listen|>

The presentation is titled "What Causes Performance Drop?" and it discusses the factors that contribute to performance degradation in named entity tagging models. The slide highlights three main hypotheses: adaptive overfitting, temporal drift, and model size.
The presenter introduces these concepts with a graph comparing CoNLL-2003 and CoNLL++ datasets, showing how different taggers perform over time. The graph includes data points for various models such as Flair, Flair Pooled, ELMo, and BERT-large, illustrating their F1 scores from 2004 to 2023.
The presenter then addresses the question of whether CoNLL-2003 taggers still work well today by presenting evidence through graphs and tables. They conclude that while there has been significant improvement in recent years due to transformer-based models like Flair, which was developed around 2018 or 2019, based on the dataset collected between 2015 and 2017.
The final part of the presentation provides contact information for further inquiries about the paper and the dataset used in the study. It also mentions that the authors are affiliated with Georgia Tech and have published papers at ACL'2023, NLP'2023, and ACL'2024.
The background image shows people walking near buildings, indicating an academic setting. Throughout the presentation, the GT logo appears consistently in the bottom right corner, reinforcing the affiliation with Georgia Tech.
The overall structure suggests this is part of a larger discussion on improving named entity recognition tasks using modern machine learning techniques.

The third frame shows a slide titled "Heterogeneous and Unknown Pay Rates," which discusses the challenges related to annotator pool composition. It lists several points such as: - Details about the annotator pool are often omitted. - Aggregating results can lead to errors due to the diversity of human annotators. - It would be interesting to compare the scores of different systems across various benchmarks like SuperGLUE 1.0 and SuperGLUE 2.0.
